===Noun===
{{en-noun|~}}

# A logical clause or phrase that a [[conditional]] statement uses. The phrase can either be [[true]] or [[false]].
# A [[requirement]] or [[requisite]].
#: {{ux|en|Environmental protection is a '''condition''' for sustainability.}} 
#: {{ux|en|What other planets might have the right '''conditions''' for life?}}
#: {{ux|en|The union had a dispute over sick time and other '''conditions''' of employment.}}
# {{lb|en|law}} A [[clause]] in a [[contract]] or [[agreement]] indicating that a certain [[contingency]] may modify the principal obligation in some way.
# The [[health]] status of a medical patient.
#: {{synonyms|en|fettle}}
#: {{ux|en|My aunt couldn’t walk up the stairs in her '''condition'''.}}
# A certain abnormal state of health; a [[malady]] or [[sickness]].<!-- Oxford English Dictionary, sense 9e: "A state of health, esp. one which is poor or abnormal; a malady or sickness." The sense outside the "esp." part is covered in the previous sense here. -->
# The [[state]] or [[quality]].
#: {{ux|en|National reports on the '''condition''' of public education are dismal.}}
#: {{ux|en|The '''condition''' of man can be classified as civilized or uncivilized.}}
#* {{RQ:Churchill Celebrity|chapter=IV|page=48|passage=Mr. Cooke at once began a tirade against the residents of Asquith for permitting a sandy and generally disgraceful '''condition''' of the roads. So roundly did he vituperate the inn management in particular, and with such a loud flow of words, that I trembled lest he should be heard on the veranda.}}
# A particular [[state]] of being.
#: {{ux|en|Hypnosis is a peculiar '''condition''' of the nervous system.}}
#: {{ux|en|Steps were taken to ameliorate the '''condition''' of slavery.}}
#: {{ux|en|Security is defined as the '''condition''' of not being threatened.}}
#: {{ux|en|Aging is a '''condition''' over which we are powerless.}}
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} The situation of a person or persons, particularly their social and/or economic class, [[rank]].
#: {{ux|en|A man of his '''condition''' has no place to make request.}}
#* {{RQ:Fielding Tom Jones|volume=VI|chapter=Containing Various Matters|page=142|passage=[T]his Zeal was now inflamed by Lady ''Bellaſton'', who had told her the preceding Evening, that ſhe was well ſatiſfied from the Conduct of ''Sophia'', and from her Carriage to his Lordſhip, that all Delays would be dangerous, and that the only Way to ſucceed, was to preſs the Match forward with ſuch Rapidity, that the young Lady ſhould have no Time to reflect, and be obliged to conſent while ſhe ſcarce knew what ſhe did. In which Manner, ſhe ſaid, one half of the Marriages among People of '''Condition''' were brought about.}}

